Text.SourceString: Have you checked out the diving yet?
Oh, that machine at the pier?//Yeah, it’s old technology.
It’ll be good to get all the trash in the ocean cleaned up, won’t it?//For one thing, we’ll actually be able to see how the coral reefs are doing and monitor their health.
But that’s far in the future.//Right now, we just have to focus on getting the ocean floor around this island cleared.
Once you have five bottles of the same kelp, bring them over to me.//I can help you with boosting your farm output.
There will be a fee, of course!
I read a study saying music can help attract fish and repopulate dying coral reefs.
I want to do that here one day, incorporating music into my study.//But not before making sure we tackle pollution in our water first.
Once you have five bottles of the same kelp, bring them over to me.//I can help you with boosting your farm output.
There will be a fee, of course!
While you’re diving, remember to collect some kelp.//It comes in handy on the farm.
Don’t worry, the kelp around this island is considered a renewable resource.//<portrait=normal>It has a very high growth rate compared to land crops.
Little things help our planet, too.//Bringing home your trash after a beach day is a great start.
You can actively prevent the trash from being eaten by turtles or sea mammals that way.
It’ll be good to get all the trash in the ocean cleaned up, won’t it?//For one thing, we’ll actually be able to see how the coral reefs are doing and monitor their health.
But that’s far in the future.//Right now, we just have to focus on getting the ocean floor around this island cleared.
When I have some free time – now keep in mind, I don’t have a lot of it – but when I do, I like to knit. It’s surprisingly relaxing.
Oh, many kinds!//<portrait=happy>Hats, beanies, wool scarfs, clothes for my dolls. A lot more.
You can find kelp in the ocean.//There’s a spot near the inn that you can dive from. Collect some, will you?//Kelp is very useful on a farm.
Don’t worry, the kelp around this island is considered a renewable resource.//<portrait=normal>It has a very high growth rate compared to land crops.

Once you have five bottles of the same kelp, bring them over to me.//I can help you with boosting your farm output.
There will be a fee, of course!
I read a study saying music can help attract fish and repopulate dying coral reefs.
I want to do that here one day, incorporating music into my study.//But not before making sure we tackle pollution in our water first.
Little things help our planet, too.//Bringing home your trash after a beach day is a great start.
You can actively prevent the trash from being eaten by turtles or sea mammals that way.
I’ve always wanted to be a scientist, of course.//I used to spend my days reading books about sea life and coral reef restoration.
I got lucky and found my house for cheap, so I bought it as soon as I could.//I’ve made it my life’s mission to improve the ocean environment around here ever since.
People take their dolls out for tea and such. It’s a thing, you know?!//Mine just sit behind the glass door sadly.
Coral reefs are my babies.//I just like to look at my doll collection.
The thing about <NPCName>Randy</> and me is we bond over our commitment to education.
I’d like to think we’re both passionate public servants… And that’s why we click.//Our goals are the same.
I’m going to see <NPCName>Bree</> at her vineyard tomorrow.//<portrait=happy>Catch up over some cheese and olives.
<NPCName>Bree</> wants to see things change on Coral Island and is proactive about finding ways to make it happen.//I like talking to her about possibilities for improving our island.
Green kelp is the easiest to come by. It’s also the cheapest kind if you sell it raw.
My lab can help you upgrade all kinds of things.//<portrait=normal>The quality of your seeds, for one.
We rely on government funding and private donations to run.
Yes, right. I meant the lab.//I suppose I’m grateful… I’m glad our government is paying attention to the coral reef issue.
We rely on government funding and private donations to run.
Yeah, right. I meant the lab.//I’m grateful, I suppose… I’m pleased that our government pays a lot of attention to the coral reefs issue.
Once you find a beacon and clean it, it will transfer data directly to the lab.//<portrait=happy>Neat, right?

I like to think that we both are passionate public servants… And that’s why we click so much.//Our goal is aligned.
We’re closed today.//If you need anything from the lab, come back tomorrow morning. I’ll be there first thing.
Sure, you can try going there now. <NPCName>Surya</> might be there.//But I really doubt it.
People take their dolls out for tea and such. It’s a thing, you know?!//Mine just sit behind the glass door sadly.
Coral reefs are my babies.//I just like to look at my doll collection.
I’m very lucky to have found my passion so young and be able to devote my life to it.
It’s sad, but I can’t really see myself doing anything else but this.//It wouldn’t be fulfilling, to me, at least.
I usually go to <NPCName>Theo</> if I need a specific specimen from the sea.
Oh! You’d help too? Thanks.//I’ll mail you a request sometime, then.
Having <NPCName>Bree</> on our side definitely helps.//With her connections, she’s the only one who can get as much funding as she does.
Yes, coral reefs. I was talking about Coral Island and how we can improve the ocean environment.//Because you know, <PlayerName>$player</>… It isn’t cheap.
Exposing coral reefs to oil can kill them, or at least slow down their growth.//It doesn’t matter whether it’s a small amount of oil over a long time or a large amount for a brief period.
A good thing to keep in mind when you go diving, <PlayerName>$player</>, is that the kelp’s color indicates its rarity.
I hope you make good use of the diving suit.
I usually go to <NPCName>Theo</> if I need a specific specimen from the sea.
Oh! You’d help too? Thanks.//I’ll mail you a request sometime, then.
I don’t suppose you know how to make smoked salmon?//Slimy stuff, but <NPCName>Jim</> loves it, you know.
Careful making it, though.//It leaves a strong smell on your hands that lasts for days.
You may find some valuable things while diving.
I’m very lucky to have found my passion so young.//Some people never do.
It’s sad, but I can’t really see myself doing anything else but this.//It wouldn’t be fulfilling, to me, at least.

Careful making it, though.//It leaves a strong smell on your hands that lasts for days.
A good thing to keep in mind when you go diving, <PlayerName>$player</>, is that the kelp’s color indicates its rarity.
Exposing coral reefs to oil can kill them, or at least slow down their growth.//It doesn’t matter whether it’s a small amount of oil over a long time or a large amount for a brief period.
There may be some valuable things that you can find by diving.
Oil spills can be very damaging to coral reefs.//It can stop their growth and affect the entire ecosystem. The fish, crabs… Everything.
I hope the big companies can see this and stop doing it.//It’s heartbreaking.
Kelp is full of nutrients that can be beneficial to our environment.
For instance, the kelp forest is just like our forest.//It provides a stable home to many species.
An oil-drilling company has been looking into my lab’s work lately and asked me about the state of our coral reefs.//I think it could be the same company that’s moving in this Summer.
Oh, I’m sorry. Not this Summer. It’s earlier than that.//I think it’s actually next week. Pufferfish, is it?
The snow may have melted, but it’s still freezing around here!
Some kelp is very rare. Sometimes, I’ll put in a request to <NPCName>Theo</> and still can’t get any.
It’s my good friend <NPCName>Walter</>’s birthday tomorrow.//What should I give him, do you think?
No mushrooms. I don’t think he likes them very much.
I don’t plan to work tomorrow. Festivals give me a reason to take a break.
All right, maybe I’ll stop by the lab after the festival for a bit if time allows.
You can do your own kelp extraction at home if you want to be economical.
You just need to make an extractor.
You can do your own kelp extraction at home if you want to be economical.
You just need to craft an extractor.
You can break open treasure chests you find at sea.
Who knows, they might have valuable items inside.
You can break open treasure chests you find at sea.
Who knows, they might have valuable items inside.
It’s sad to see how much trash there is at sea, isn’t it?//It’s unfortunate.
I donate the scarves and beanies I knit during the year to a shelter on the other side of the island.//I hope they can use them.
I always try to donate before Winter hits. Just whatever I knit that year.//Usually the Mayor and <NPCName>Bree</> have things for me to send, too.
I donate the scarves and beanies I knit during the year to a shelter on the other side of the island.//I hope they can use them.
I always try to donate before Winter hits. Just whatever I knit that year.//Usually the Mayor and <NPCName>Bree</> have things for me to send, too.
My ears get cold in Winter… *sigh*
Aren’t you cold, <PlayerName>$player</>?
I’m happy with the progress we’ve made this year.//I’m excited to see what the New Year can bring to our island.
I’m excited about the prospect of heat-resistant coral reefs.//I feel like it will make a massive difference in the ecosystem.
Of course, we need to also fight pollution, too.
*zoning out*
Oh! Was I sleeping with my eyes open again?
Thankfully, my house isn’t too far a walk from the lab.
I better hurry.
*zoning out*
Oh! Was I sleeping with my eyes open again?
I should probably go home and check to make sure the house is still standing.
Meh… Checking won’t make any difference.//What good would I be, anyway? It’s not like I can prevent it from happening.
I better hurry.
Ugh… The rain is so heavy. Now the house makes weird noises.//It’s pretty solid, though.
I hope, anyway.
I wear the same beanie every year.//Why replace something that’s still good, right?
Seems like it’s snowing pretty hard outside.
Saturday is a good day to take off.
Anyway, I can’t work at my best if I don’t take a break every now and then.
It’s a bit stuffy here this time of year, isn’t it?
Unfortunately, we need to keep the windows shut. I have to be sure there’s no contamination.
There’s no need for me to concentrate when I knit.
It’s kind of nice, actually. Especially after a long day of focusing on work.
Knitting helps to keep your joints healthy… Did you know that?
It’s not just that. It helps your joints while exercising your brain.
I almost always lived by myself when I was young, and I didn’t think I was lonely until I had company.
I guess I was so used to being alone, I didn’t know any other way.
I started to knit in grade school.
I had a hard time concentrating on math homework until I started knitting while thinking about a problem.
I never found the time to redecorate this house. Good thing <NPCName>Leah</> gives it the attention it needs.
This is all her, you know.
<NPCName>Leah</> is very perceptive about beauty, fashion, and stuff like that.
Quite a talent she inherited from her mother, I think.
Do you know <NPCName>Walter</> well? He used to practice law in the city.
Oh, that was long before <NPCName>Luke</> was even born. I heard that’s where he met <NPCName>Bree</>.
It’s okay to unwind once in a while, but everything in moderation.
It’s hard to think about work in this weather.
I’m here to get my flu shot, with the colder weather arriving. Better safe than sorry, I think.
*achoo!*
I think I got the flu, but I’m not too sure. I’m going to see what <NPCName>Charles</> thinks.
Just in case, don’t get too close.
